	<http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/name> "በቴርጌላ፡ ማርያም፡"@gez , "Batergelā Māryām"@gez , "ቤቴርጌላ፡ ማርያም፡"@gez , "Betergelā Māryām"@gez , "በርቴግላ፡ ማርያም፡"@gez , "Bartegǝlā Māryām"@gez , "በትረ፡ ጌላ፡ ማርያም፡"@gez , "Batra Gelā Māryām"@gez , "\n                  ʾabbā\n               " .
_:bd7806fd74af2c6ceb1018c764b6a6b9 a <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E52_Time-span> ;
	<http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P78_is_identified_by> " He was a medieval saint referred to as a son of the prince. \n                   As a child he was imprisoned and tortured together with his brothers on the order of his own father. \n                     The account resembles  stories that are told in the royal Ethiopian chronicles, where it said that \n                   \n                     \n                     ʾaṣe Zarʾa Yāʿqob acted resolutely \n                   against his sons after charges were made \n                     against them that they were practicing pagan rites. \n                     Thus, Batra Gelā Māryām could possibly be identified with   \n                 \n                     \n                     ʾaṣe Baʾǝda Māryām I, \n                   son and successor of   \n                 \n                       \n                     ʾaṣe Zarʾa Yāʿqob. \n                   His acts are only preserved in the form of three miracles in the Taʾammǝra Māryām. The name is attested only in the variants \n                   በቴርጌላ፡ ማርያም፡, ቤቴርጌላ፡ ማርያም፡ and በርቴግላ፡ ማርያም፡. \n                    proposes the reconstruction በትረ፡ ጌላ፡ ማርያም፡.\n               " .
